Children.Text:
The APSIM Chickpea model has been developed from the original APSIM Chickpea model described by [robertson_simulation_2002] using the Plant Modelling Framework of [brown_plant_2014].

Note to users:
Desi and Kabuli chickpea are two subspecies of chickpea. The variety set includes both types. As indicated by Peake et al., 2021 (GRDC Updates), there was less confidence in predicting

Children.Text: Requires 5 days of temp above 16 degrees (or ten days at 15 degrees) before 1cm pods are visible, due to sensitivity of pod initiation to mean daily temperature (see Srinivasan et al. 1998; Clarke and Siddique, 2004). These days may accumulate anytime after flowering begins (i.e. during previous growth stage as well as during the current one). so the 'EndFloweringPodStartTT' is subtracted from the 5 days target

Retranslocation = movement of reserves out of live organs.
Reallocation = from senesced organs

Storage fraction decides how much is available to be moved, while these decide what proportion can be moved each day

Children.Text: Using soybean data from Flenet et al 1996 to establish trend, with data from Tesfaye et al 2006 for absolute values (close to 0.8 at 40cm RS). These high values also agreed with Thomas and Fukai 1995 (their measurements were at noon therefore they need to be increased for absolute light interception?). ICRISAT provided Ext coefficients at standard row spacings
Children.Name: Memo

Children.Text: There is no specific TE parameter in NextGen. TE is an emergent property calculated separately from water use and biomass production
Children.Name: memo

Children.Text:
Ayaz eta 2004 presented a RUE of 1.6 g/MJ PAR during non-limiting temperature conditions for field pea.  Halving this to make it total radiation gives 0.8 g/MJ and adding 20% to account for root and  nodule production and N fixiation costs gives 1.0 g/MJ

However Sincalir had data that presented RUE of 2.0 hence by the same calcs we have advanced RUE to 1.2
